Sep 8 2009 	Number One Hotel in San Francisco	We usually stay at the Four Seasons while in San Francisco; we thought we would try a different place and noticed that for less money, we got a one-bedroom suite complete with kitchen. I was expecting a good stay, and hoping that the service would match the top notch service at the Four Seasons.Overall, we were blown away by this property. I cannot say enough about the staff, who almost glow as it seems they love their jobs so much. Either that, or they are very good actors. Some taxi drivers still do not know about this place and we were taken to the other Fairmont by mistake, so give them the address in addition to the property name. The location is quite good, near the Russian Hill area, and many good restaurants are within a 15-20 minute walk. The (free!!!) house limo will take you anywhere within a 2 mile radius, plus PICK YOU UP, which is almost unheard of.The property is stunning -- the pictures on their website do not do it justice. We were upgraded to a two-bedroom, but it was at ground level and by the makeshift gym (they are still working on the gym and Willow Stream Spa) and the exit out to Ghirardelli Square. So, during the day, it was fairly noisy --plenty of slamming doors, plus I don't think they put in triple pane windows as you can clearly hear conversations on the street of passersby, and street traffic. If you are on the Ghirardelli Square side, you have to deal with the noise from the nearby businesses and tourists. However, by evening, the noise is diminished quite significantly. We did not hear any noise from the other suites beside or above us. If you do not like big city noises, I would not recommend staying here.We found the bed in the master bedroom fairly soft (we like firm beds) and we moved into the second bedroom for the remainder of our stay as the bed seemed firmer. We asked the staff if they could put a board under the mattress, but that was the only request they could not accomodate.Both bathrooms were gorgeous, with plenty of soft, fluffy towels. Shower pressure could have been a bit stronger, and though high-end, the amentities were strongly scented with a men's cologne type fragrance, which was disappointing for me.The kitchen was extremely well equipped and what impressed me were all the high-end touches; Henckel knives, Cuisinart cookware, and Villeroy and Boch dishware, plus a Wolf gas range. They spared no expense outfitting these kitchens and I only wish I had time to cook during our stay. There was also a Bosch washer and dryer in the suite, so you can pack light and leave room in your suitcase instead for shopping. Detergent and dryer sheets are provided.There are two business centres with internet access (free for guests) and free Wifi throughout the property, though I found it very spotty in our suite. There are also two terraces with propane firepits which overlook Ghirardelli Square and the ocean. The daily wine and cheese is sponsored by the sales staff, and we appreciated that they were very discreet re: sales They seemed to notice when people weren't interested and were pleasant people to talk to, not pushy at all, plus gave us some good sightseeing tips. The continental breakfast is simple, but again, very high-end; fresh squeezed juice, Illy coffee, organic tea, Ghirardelli hot chocolate, organic yogurts, beautiful pastries, and plenty of cut-up fresh fruit. It made a great start to our day.If it seems like I'm raving about this place, I am! We would return in a heartbeat, trust me, it may seem pricey but for the service and amenities, it is really good value. This is going to be our new favorite hotel in San Francisco.	
